
[1]per

   PER, a Latin preposition, denoting through, passing,or over the whole
   extent, as in perambulo. Hence it is sometimes equivalent to very in
   English, as in peracutus, very sharp. As a prefix, in English, it
   retains these significations, and in chimistry it is used to denote
   very of fully, to the utmost extent, as in peroxyd,a substance oxydated
   to the utmost degree.

   Per is used also for by, as per bearer, by the bearer.

   Per annum, [L.] by the year; in each year successively.

   Per se, [L.] by himself; by itself; by themselves.
